misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that shifting right by saving the last element, moving the remaining elements one index to the right (from the end toward the start), then placing the saved last element at index 0 will correctly implement a one-position right shift with wrap-around.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: No conceptual gap detected here: this matches Java’s actual array indexing and assignment semantics. The program reads N integers, performs an in-place right shift correctly (iterating from high index down to 1 to avoid overwriting needed values), wraps the last element to the front, and prints the resulting array in the required format.
